                  <handDesc><handNote xml:id="h1" script="Ethiopic"><seg type="rubrication">
                    <ref target="#ms_i1.4 #ms_i1.5"/>
                    <foreign xml:lang="gez">ማርያም፡</foreign></seg></handNote></handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                    <decoNote type="miniature" xml:id="d1"><locus target="#1r" facs="001">Fol. 1r</locus><desc><ref type="authFile" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/AT1031VirginAndChild">Virgin and Child</ref> with caption <q>"Saint Michael,” “With her beloved Son,” “Saint Gabriel.”</q></desc></decoNote>
                    <decoNote type="miniature" xml:id="d2"><locus target="#71v" facs="072">Fol. 71v</locus><desc><ref type="authFile" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/AT1035HolyMan">Holy Man Portrait</ref> <persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS4306GabraMa">Gabra Manfas Qǝddus</persName> with caption <q>"How our father, Gäbrä Mänfäs Qǝddus, prayed,” “Lions,”  “Tigers”</q></desc></decoNote>
                    <decoNote type="miniature" xml:id="d3"><locus target="#167v" facs="168">Fol. 167v</locus><desc><ref type="authFile" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/AT1035HolyMan">Holy Man Portrait</ref>,<persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS4585Georgeo">St George of Lydda</persName> and the <term key="dragon" ana="#dragon"/> with caption <q>“Icon of Saint George,” “dragon.”</q></desc></decoNote>
                    <decoNote type="frame" xml:id="d04">
                      Decorative designs:
                      <locus target="#37r #45v #52r #82v #151r" facs="037 046 052 083 151">folss. 37r, 45v, 52r, 82v, 151r, </locus> (ḥaräg in red ink);
                      <locus target="#62r #74r #88v #113v" facs="062 074 089 114">62r, 74r, 88v, 113v, </locus> (ḥaräg in red and black ink);
                      <locus target="#116v #123r #150r" facs="117 123 150">116v, 123r, 150r, </locus> (alternating red and black dots);
                      <locus target="#129r #143r" facs="129 143">129r, 143r, </locus> (multiple full stops between alternating red and black dotted lines);
                      <locus target="#162r #167r" facs="162 167">162r, 167r</locus> (multiple full stops</decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
                  <additions><list>
                  <item xml:id="e1"><desc><locus target="#1v" facs="002">Fol. 1v</locus> disorganized lettering; possibly writing practice.</desc></item>
                  <item xml:id="e2"><desc><locus target="#13v" facs="014">Fol. 13v</locus> writing in bottom right margin.</desc></item>
                  <item xml:id="a1"><desc>
                    The original scribal hand has included a set of instructions for the recitation of certain Psalms:
                    <locus target="#29r" facs="029">fols. 29r, </locus> (“Recite [psalm 35, ET] with honey and drink it and your enemy will flee”),
                    <locus target="#31r" facs="031">31r, </locus> (“recite  [Psalm 37, ET] seven times with water in public”),
                    <locus target="#37r" facs="037">37r, </locus> (“When someone has hemorrhage, recite [Psalm 42, ET] seven times with salt and pepper and butter”),
                    <locus target="#42r" facs="42">42r, </locus> (“For eloquent speech, recite [Psalm 49, ET] with salt”),
                    <locus target="#44v" facs="045">44v, </locus> (“recite [Psalm 51, ET] seven times with lemon.”),
                    <locus target="#68r" facs="068">68r, </locus> (recite [Psalm 78, ET] with dates and your speech will become eloquent”),
                    <locus target="#76r" facs="076">76r, </locus> (“Recite [Psalm 85, ET] with holy water while pronouncing your enemy’s name and pour the water on your door and your enemy will go away”),
                    <locus target="#104r" facs="104">104r</locus> (“recite [Psalm 117, ET] with salt when you miss someone [who is gone away]”), etc. </desc></item>
                  <item xml:id="e3"><desc><locus target="#42r" facs="042">Fol. 42r</locus> disorganized lettering on right margin and commentary in bottom margin.</desc></item>
                  <item xml:id="e4"><desc><locus target="#54r" facs="054">Fol. 54r</locus> disorganized lettering on right margin.</desc></item>
                  <item xml:id="e5"><desc><locus target="#68v" facs="069">Fol. 68v</locus> A small cross or symbol in red ink marks the midpoint of the Psalms. </desc></item>
                  <item xml:id="e6"><desc><locus target="#129v" facs="130">Fol. 129v</locus> disorganized lettering throughout otherwise blank folio.</desc></item>
                  <item xml:id="e7"><desc><locus target="#150v" facs="151">Fol. 150v</locus> erased text and crude drawings. </desc></item>
                  <item xml:id="a2"><desc type="OwnershipNote"><locus target="#167r" facs="167">Fol. 167r</locus> Name of the owner: ? Krǝstos (the first name is erased). </desc></item>
                  <item xml:id="e8"><desc>Binding is original and intact.</desc></item>
                  <item xml:id="e9"><desc>Vellum is in fair condition. Front and back folios show more wear and discoloration.</desc></item>
                  <item xml:id="e10"><desc>
                    words of text are written interlinearly (<locus target="#13r #36v #43v #47r" facs="013 037 044 047">folss. 13r, 36v, 43v, 47r, </locus>, etc.);
                    and lines of text are written interlinearly (<locus target="#7v #21r #36r #47r" facs="008 021 036 047">7v, 21r, 36r, 47r, </locus>, etc.);
                    and in the upper margin with a symbol (+) marking the location where the text is to be inserted
                    (<locus target="#167r" facs="167">167r, </locus> f. 167r, col. 1, line 15);
                    erasure markings are visible (<locus target="#14r #27v #42r #108r #147r" facs="014 028 042 108 147">14r, 27v, 42r, 108r, 147r, </locus>, etc.);
                    text has been removed (e.g., <locus target="#13r #57v" facs="013 058">13r, 57v</locus>).</desc></item>
                  <item xml:id="e11"><desc>This scribe has avoided the problem of lines of text too long to fit on one line by adopting an aspect ratio that leaves ample room for the width of most lines. Occasionally a line is too long and is completed above or below the end of the line. (e.g., ff. 8v, 40v, 114r).</desc></item>
                  </list></additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                    <binding xml:id="binding" contemporary="partly">
                        <decoNote xml:id="b1">Parchment, 170 x 160 x 70 mm, four Coptic chain stitches attached with bridle attachments to rough-hewn wooden boards, front cover is cracked and has been repaired.</decoNote>
                        <decoNote xml:id="b2" type="bindingMaterial">
                           <material key="parchment"/>
                           <material key="wood"/>
                        </decoNote>
                    </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
